{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ChCybwK6whrsiiA9BENgo6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I found the issue! Looking at lines 8146-8160:\n\n```rust\nKeyword::ARRAY => {\n    if dialect_of!(self is SnowflakeDialect) {\n        Ok(DataType::Array(ArrayElemTypeDef::None))\n    } else if dialect_of!(self is ClickHouseDialect) {\n        Ok(self.parse_sub_type(|internal_type| {\n            DataType::Array(ArrayElemTypeDef::Parenthesis(internal_type))\n        })?)\n    } else {\n        self.expect_token(&Token::Lt)?;\n        ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor `SnowflakeDialect`, `ARRAY` is parsed as `DataType::Array(ArrayElemTypeDef::None)` without consuming any type parameter, but the SQL has `CAST(\"col_14\" AS ARRAY(DECIMAL(38, 0)))` which needs the parenthesized element type parsed. The parser returns immediately after seeing `ARRAY` without consuming the `(DECIMAL(38, 0))` part.\n\nThe issue is that after parsing `ARRAY`, the parser expects `)` to close the CAST but finds `(` instead. I need to check if the next token is `(` after `ARRAY` in Snowflake and consume the parenthesized type if present, similar to how `ClickHouseDialect` handles this with `parse_sub_type`. Though Snowflake's `ARRAY` type typically doesn't take type parameters in standard usage, this SQL suggests it might need to support that syntax. in some versions or SQL contexts, `ARRAY(type)` might be used.\n\nLet me check: the files `2a2ef329e042.sql` and `34054e52ec12.sql` are in `unparsed_snowflake/` but the `ARRAY(DECIMAL(38, 0))` syntax might be something that Snowflake actually supports or that was incorrectly tagged.\n\nFor the purposes of making this parse, the simplest fix is:\n- After `ARRAY` in Snowflake dialect, if the next token is `(`, try to parse `ARRAY(type)` as a parameterized array type.\n\nThis would be similar to what ClickHouse does.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The `ClickHouseDialect` case uses `parse_sub_type` which parses `(type)`. I could modify the SnowflakeDialect case to first attempt parsing without parameters, then check if parentheses follow to parse the type inside them. Modifying the Snowflake array parsing logic... I'm seeing the issue now—GenericDialect expects `<` after `ARRAY` for the type parameter syntax, but when it encounters `(` instead, it fails with \"Expected <, found: (\". SnowflakeDialect handles this by returning early without consuming the parentheses, which leaves the `(...)` unparsed. I need to check if extending this fix to GenericDialect would help with the failing test cases.\n\nLooking at the actual failures, some are related to `COPY GRANTS (col_list)` appearing before the SELECT body, which is a separate parsing issue from the `ARRAY(type)` syntax. Let me focus on fixing the Snowflake case first by adding proper handling for the parenthesized type, then see if that resolves the test failures.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1118,"cache_read_input_tokens":136060,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1118},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c43ed8a1-1b85-4dfe-81fe-8f9500711026","uuid":"9ea70e10-1df7-42c6-bfb3-2028db7337f3"}
